39 SUBPART II-B. HURRICANE HELENE LOCAL GOVERNMENT CAPITAL GRANT
40 PROGRAM
41 SECTION 2B.1.(a) Establishment. – There is established the Hurricane Helene
42 Local Government Capital Grant Program (Program) to be administered by the Office of State
43 Budget and Management. The purpose of the Program is to disburse grants to eligible recipients
44 for capital projects in the affected area in accordance with the Program requirements set forth in
45 this section.
46 SECTION 2B.1.(b) Criteria; Uses. – OSBM shall disburse grants to eligible
47 recipients under a damage per capita formula developed from FEMA's damage estimates and
48 reports in the affected area from Hurricane Helene. The grants shall be used for capital projects
49 to repair, renovate, or replace infrastructure damaged by Hurricane Helene. These capital projects
50 must be projects that have been denied eligibility for FEMA Public Assistance reimbursement.
House Bill 1012-Third Edition Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 2B.1.(c) Eligible Recipients. – To be eligible for a grant under the
2 Program, a recipient shall be a unit of local government or a federally recognized tribe on lands
3 held in trust by the United States located in the affected area.
4 SECTION 2B.1.(d) Prioritization. – OSBM shall prioritize grants to an eligible
5 recipient with a population of 300,000 or fewer based on the 2023 Certified County Population
6 Estimates from the State Demographer and that qualify, in whole or in part, for FEMA Public
7 Assistance Categories C through G.
8 SECTION 2B.1.(e) Maximum Grant Awards. – OSBM shall not award more than
9 the following percentages of the funds appropriated for the Program:
10 (1) Twenty percent (20%) to one county, including grants to units of local
11 government within that county.
12 (2) Five percent (5%) per eligible recipient.
13 (3) Five percent (5%) per zip code if that zip code only qualifies for FEMA Public
14 Assistance Categories A through B.
15 SECTION 2B.1.(f) Reporting Requirement. – OSBM shall submit a report to the
16 chairs of the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on General Government and the Joint
17 Legislative Emergency Management Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division no
18 later than six months after the application period for this Program opens, and every six months
19 thereafter until all funds are expended. The report shall include, at a minimum, all of the
20 following:
21 (1) The number of grants disbursed and to which eligible recipients.
22 (2) The proposed uses for each grant.
23 (3) The average and median amounts of the grants disbursed under the Program.
24
25 SUBPART II-C. HURRICANE HELENE FLOOD MITIGATION GRANT PROGRAM
26 SECTION 2C.1.(a) Establishment. – There is established the Hurricane Helene
27 Flood Mitigation Grant Program (Program). The funds appropriated in this act to NCEM for the
28 Disaster Relief and Mitigation Fund (DRMF) shall be used to provide funds to the Program to
29 provide flood mitigation grants to units of local government and nonprofit organizations to
30 undertake flood mitigation projects in the affected area. Units of local government may also apply
31 for engineering assistance grants.
32 SECTION 2C.1.(b) Flood Mitigation Grants. – Grants disbursed under the Program
33 for eligible flood mitigation grants must be for projects that reduce the risk of future damage
34 from flooding through structural or nonstructural measures through the following:
35 (1) Culvert or bridge retrofits or replacements.
36 (2) Stormwater and drainage system improvements.
37 (3) Relocation of at-risk infrastructure.
38 (4) Hardening of critical facilities and utilities.
39 SECTION 2C.1.(c) Engineering Assistance Grants. – Grants disbursed under the
40 Program may also be used by units of local government to identify and design shovel-ready
41 projects related to flood mitigation.
42 SECTION 2C.1.(d) Cost-Share. – There is no cost-share or matching requirement
43 by recipients to receive grants under the Program. Recipients of grants will be paid under a
44 reimbursement model for costs incurred for eligible flood mitigation or engineering assistance
45 grants.
46 SECTION 2C.1.(e) Maximum Grant Awards. – NCEM shall not award a grant
47 larger than (i) ten percent (10%) to a single recipient or (ii) twenty percent (20%) to a single
48 county, of the total amount of funds appropriated in this act for the Program.
49 SECTION 2C.1.(f) Administrative Expenses. – NCEM may retain up to one and
50 one-half percent (1.5%) of the funds appropriated for the Program created by this section for
51 administrative expenses.
