4 SUBPART II-D. AERIAL ASSET ACCESSIBILITY GRANT PROGRAM
5 SECTION 2D.1.(a) Program; Purpose. – There is established the Aerial Asset
6 Accessibility Grant Program (Program) to be administered by NCEM. The purpose of the
7 Program is to disburse grants to local airports in the affected area to (i) repair, replace, and restore
8 infrastructure damaged by Hurricane Helene and (ii) build and improve capacity for emergency
9 preparedness and disaster response for future natural disasters and emergencies. NCEM shall
10 consult with the Department of Transportation if grant applications concern airport roads or other
11 infrastructure, as necessary.
12 SECTION 2D.1.(b) Grants for Damaged Infrastructure. – NCEM shall disburse
13 grants to eligible recipients to repair, replace, and restore infrastructure on airport property,
14 including terminals, runways, gates, hangars, curtilage structures, airport roads, and other
15 structures damaged by Hurricane Helene. Applicants for these grants must pursue insurance
16 coverage and federal aid prior to being awarded a grant for these purposes.
17 SECTION 2D.1.(c) Grants for Capacity for Emergency Preparedness. – NCEM shall
18 disburse grants to eligible recipients to improve the capacity for emergency preparedness and
19 disaster response through capital projects and infrastructure and communication improvements
20 on airfield property. Eligible recipients must demonstrate how the project or improvement will
21 increase emergency preparedness and disaster response.
22 SECTION 2D.1.(d) Eligible Recipient. – An eligible recipient for a grant awarded
23 under this Program shall be limited to persons or units of local government that own an airport
24 that (i) is currently in operation or (ii) was in operation prior to Hurricane Helene and not
25 currently in operation but for damage from Hurricane Helene and meets the following criteria:
26 (1) Must have a fuel truck available 24 hours per day and seven days per week.
27 (2) The county in which the airport resides must enter into an agreement with the
28 State giving the State untethered access to any facilities provided under the
29 Program.
30 (3) Must have on-site aviation mechanics that offer services to the public.
31 (4) During a state of emergency, the airport must be able to be open 24 hours per
32 day and seven days per week.
33 (5) Does not offer passenger service.
34 SECTION 2D.1.(e) Prioritization. – NCEM shall prioritize applicants with facilities
35 that demonstrate adequate runway capacity, storage capacity, and personnel that can substantially
36 contribute to enhanced regional emergency and disaster readiness. These prioritized applicants
37 shall also be capable of facilitating access of various forms and sizes of aircraft providing
38 adequate takeoff and landing clearance.
39 SECTION 2D.1.(f) Maximum Grant Award. – Grants awarded under this Program
40 shall not exceed three million dollars ($3,000,000) per eligible recipient. A county in the affected
41 area shall not receive more than two grants from the Program.
42 SECTION 2D.1.(g) Reporting Requirement. – NCEM shall submit a report to the
43 chairs of the Joint Legislative Emergency Management Oversight Committee and the Fiscal
44 Research Division no later than six months after the application period for this Program opens,
45 and every six months thereafter until all funds are expended. The report shall include, at a
46 minimum, all of the following:
47 (1) The number of grants disbursed and to which eligible recipients.
48 (2) The proposed uses for each grant.
49 (3) The average and median amounts of the grants disbursed under the Program.
50
51 SUBPART II-E. DAM SAFETY GRANT FUND
House Bill 1012-Third Edition Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 2E.1. Part 3 of Article 21 of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes is
2 amended by adding a new section to read:
3 "§ 143-215.32B. Dam Safety Grant Fund.
4 (a) Creation; Purpose. – There is created within the Department a special, nonreverting
5 account to be known as the Dam Safety Grant Fund to issue grants from the Fund to eligible dam
6 owners for the purpose of dam repair, modification, or removal, if the dam was damaged by a
7 natural disaster. The Fund shall be administered by the Division of Energy, Mineral, and Land
8 Resources.
9 (b) Prioritization. – The Department shall assign priority for grants that serve as the State
10 match to eligible projects based on the Risk-Based Prioritization Method established under the
11 Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) High Hazard Potential Dams (HHPD)
12 Rehabilitation Grant Program. Funds may also be used for dams not eligible for federal match
13 under the HHPD Rehabilitation Grant Program if the dam was damaged by a natural disaster and
14 classified as high hazard.
15 (c) The Department shall, when funding is available, administer grants from the Fund in
16 a manner consistent with applicable federal and State law and regulations.
17 (d) The Department shall submit an annual report to the Joint Legislative Oversight
18 Committee on Agriculture and Natural and Economic Resources detailing the projects funded,
19 federal dollars drawn from the HHPD Rehabilitation Grant Program for those projects, and
20 locations, types, and justification of each project."
21
22 PART III. ADDITIONAL BUDGETARY FUNDING AVAILABILITY AND
23 REGULATION
24 SECTION 3.1.(a) Competitive Grant Prioritization. – Notwithstanding any other
25 provision of law, for the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium, the following programs and funds, which
26 collectively represent over seven hundred fifty million dollars ($750,000,000) in the base budget
27 from competitive grant programs over the biennium, shall prioritize applicants from counties that
28 (i) were designated, in whole or in part, by the United States Department of Housing and Urban
29 Development as the most impacted and distressed counties from Hurricane Helene and (ii) have
30 a population of 300,000 or fewer based upon the 2023 Certified County Population Estimates
31 from the State Demographer:
32 (1) Needs-Based Public School Capital Fund, established in Article 38B of
33 Chapter 115C of the General Statutes. The matching requirement under
34 G.S. 115C-546.11 is waived for applicants qualifying under this subsection
35 for prioritization.
36 (2) Community Health Grant Program administered by the Department of Health
37 and Human Services, Division of Central Management, Office of Rural Health
38 (Rural Health).
39 (3) State-Designated Rural Health Centers Support Grant Program and Rural
40 Health Capital Grants Program administered by Rural Health.
41 (4) Agricultural Water Resources Assistance Program, established under Article
42 5 of Chapter 139 of the General Statutes.
43 (5) Utility Account, established under G.S. 143B-437.01.
44 (6) Rural Engagement & Investment Program under the Department of
45 Commerce, Rural Economic Development Division.
46 (7) State and local projects funded from the Parks and Recreation Trust Fund,
47 established under G.S. 143B-135.56.
48 (8) North Carolina Land and Water Fund, established under G.S. 143B-135.234.
49 (9) Grants administered by the North Carolina Arts Council, established under
50 Part 14 of Article 2 of Chapter 143B of the General Statutes.
Page 10 House Bill 1012-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (10) Grants awarded by the State Water Infrastructure Authority from the State
2 Drinking Water and Wastewater Reserves.
3 SECTION 3.1.(b) Applicants. – Each agency overseeing the administration of funds
4 from the programs and funds listed in subsection (a) of this section shall require applicants
5 seeking prioritization to attest that (i) the application for funds is for repair, replacement, or
6 construction of equipment, buildings, or natural features due to damage or effects from Hurricane
7 Helene, including capacity-building, and (ii) the amount of funds requested is the amount of
8 unmet need above the amount paid by insurance and available federal aid.
9 SECTION 3.2.(a) Federal Funds for Water and Sewer Projects. – The General
10 Assembly finds that the supplemental appropriations provided by Congress in the American
11 Relief Act of 2025 (P.L. 118-158) and allocated by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
12 to the Clean Water State Revolving Fund and the Drinking Water State Revolving Fund for
13 wastewater treatment works, drinking water facilities, and decentralized wastewater treatment
14 systems in the State impacted by Hurricane Helene should be expeditiously used for repair and
15 replacement of drinking water and wastewater infrastructure damaged by Hurricane Helene.
16 Accordingly, the General Assembly appropriates in this act for the 2025-2026 fiscal
17 year the sum of six hundred eighty-five million six hundred thirteen thousand dollars
18 ($685,613,000) in federal disaster funding in this act, which is allocated in and for the following
19 amounts and uses:
20 (1) Two hundred fifty-three million six hundred eighty-one thousand dollars
21 ($253,681,000) to the Clean Water State Revolving Fund established in
22 G.S. 159G-22(b) (CWSRF) and four hundred nine million four hundred
23 twenty-two thousand dollars ($409,422,000) to the Drinking Water State
24 Revolving Fund established in G.S. 159G-22(c) (DWSRF) for funding of
25 projects consistent with applicable federal law and guidance to CWSRF and
26 DWSRF eligible entities that were damaged, can demonstrate impact, or
27 experienced a loss or disruption of a mission-essential function caused by
28 Hurricane Helene.
29 (2) Twenty-two million five hundred ten thousand dollars ($22,510,000) to the
30 CWSRF to improve the resilience of decentralized wastewater treatment
31 systems to flooding, to assess the potential to connect homes served by
32 decentralized wastewater treatment systems to centralized wastewater
33 systems, and to fund such connections.
34 SECTION 3.2.(b) Receipt. – These funds shall be receipted by the Department of
35 Environmental Quality in the amounts listed in subsection (a) of this section for those purposes.
36 SECTION 3.2.(c) The following entities are eligible to apply for a loan or grant from
37 funds appropriated in this act to the Clean Water State Revolving Fund for decentralized
38 wastewater treatment systems:
39 (1) A local government unit or a nonprofit water corporation, as defined in
40 G.S. 159G-20.
41 (2) A Community Development Finance Institution or a nonprofit organization
42 that provides financing assistance to homeowners to repair or replace
43 decentralized wastewater systems in North Carolina.
44 SECTION 3.3. Public School Capital. – The State Controller shall transfer interest
45 earned as of June 30, 2025, from the Needs-Based Public School Capital Fund established in
46 Article 38B of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes, estimated at thirty-nine million six hundred
47 thousand dollars ($39,600,000), to the Department of Public Instruction for Capital Recovery
48 Funds for the Public School Facilities Program, established in S.L. 2024-53, Committee Report,
49 page F2, Item 7.
50 SECTION 3.4. Emergency Flexibility of Funds. – G.S. 166A-19.40 reads as
51 rewritten:
House Bill 1012-Third Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 166A-19.40. Use of contingency and emergency funds.
2 (a) Use of Contingency and Emergency Funds. – The Governor may use contingency and
3 emergency funds:
4 (1) As necessary and appropriate to provide relief and assistance from the effects
5 of an emergency.
6 (2) As necessary and appropriate for National Guard training in preparation for
7 emergencies with the concurrence of the Council of State.
8 (b) Repealed by Session Laws 2015-241, s. 6.19(a), effective July 1, 2015.
9 (c) Use of Other Funds. – The Governor may reallocate on a nonrecurring basis such
10 other funds as may reasonably be available within the appropriations of the various departments
11 when all of the following conditions are satisfied:
12 (1) The severity and magnitude of the emergency so requires.
13 (2) Contingency and emergency funds are insufficient or inappropriate.
14 (3) A state of emergency has been declared pursuant to G.S. 166A-19.20(a).
15 (4) Funds in the State Emergency Response and Disaster Relief Fund are
16 insufficient."
17 SECTION 3.5. Extend Expiration of Tree Ordinance Restriction. – The expiration
18 date of Section 1D.8 of S.L. 2024-57, as extended by Section 5.1 of S.L. 2025-2, is extended
19 until October 1, 2025.
20
21 PART IV. REVERSION, LIMITATIONS ON USE OF FUNDS, AUDIT, AND
22 REPORTING OF FUNDS
23 SECTION 4.1.(a) Reversion. – Except as otherwise provided, funds appropriated
24 under Part II of this act shall revert to the Savings Reserve if not expended or encumbered by
25 June 30, 2030.
26 SECTION 4.1.(b) Receipt of Allocations. – A recipient of State funds under this act
27 shall use best efforts and take all reasonable steps to obtain alternative funds that cover the losses
28 or needs for which the State funds are provided, including funds from insurance policies in effect
29 and available federal aid. State funds paid under this act are declared to be excess over funds
30 received by a recipient from the settlement of a claim for loss or damage covered under the
31 recipient's applicable insurance policy in effect or federal aid. Where a recipient is an institution
32 of higher education or a non-State entity, the requirement regarding alternative funds and the
33 calculation of alternative funds received under this subsection includes seeking private donations
34 to help cover the losses or needs for which State funds are provided. An agency awarding State
35 funds for disaster relief shall include a notice to the recipient of the requirements of this
36 subsection.
37 SECTION 4.1.(c) Remittance of Funds. – If a recipient obtains alternative funds
38 pursuant to subsection (b) of this section, the recipient shall remit the funds to the State agency
39 from which the State funds were received. A recipient is not required to remit any amount in
40 excess of the State funds provided to the recipient under this act. The State agency shall transfer
41 these funds to the Savings Reserve.
42 SECTION 4.1.(d) Contract Requirements. – Any contract or other instrument
43 entered into by a recipient for receipt of funds under this act shall include the requirements set
44 forth in subsections (b) and (c) of this section.
45 SECTION 4.1.(e) Limitation on Powers of Governor. – The Governor may not use
46 the funds described in this act to make budget adjustments under G.S. 143C-6-4 or to make
47 reallocations under G.S. 166A-19.40(c). Nothing in this act shall be construed to prohibit the
48 Governor from exercising the Governor's authority under these statutes with respect to funds
49 other than those described in this act.
50 SECTION 4.1.(f) Directive. – The Governor shall ensure that funds allocated in this
51 act are expended in a manner that does not adversely affect any person's or entity's eligibility for
Page 12 House Bill 1012-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 federal funds that are made available, or that are anticipated to be made available, as a result of
2 natural disasters. The Governor shall also, to the extent practicable, avoid using State funds to
3 cover costs that will be, or likely will be, covered by federal funds.
4 SECTION 4.1.(g) Continuation of Allocation Reporting Requirements. – OSBM
5 shall add the appropriations and allocations provided for in this act to the reporting requirements
6 set forth in Section 4.1(g) of S.L. 2025-2.
7 SECTION 4.1.(h) Continuation of State Auditor Oversight. – The Office of the
8 Governor of North Carolina shall continue the reporting requirements set forth in Section 4.2 of
9 S.L. 2025-2. The State Auditor shall include all funds appropriated and allocated under this act
10 in their report to the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations and include the
11 expenditure of these funds in the public dashboard as set forth in Sections 4.2(c) and (d) of S.L.
12 2025-2.
13
14 PART V. MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS
15 SECTION 5.1. Effect of Headings. – The headings to the parts and sections of this
16 act are a convenience to the reader and are for reference only. The headings do not expand, limit,
17 or define the text of this act, except for effective dates referring to a part or section.
18 SECTION 5.2. Severability. – If any section or provision of this act is declared
19 unconstitutional or invalid by the courts, it does not affect the validity of this act as a whole or
20 any part other than the part so declared to be unconstitutional or invalid.
21 SECTION 5.3. Effective Date. – Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective
22 when it becomes law.
